<article>
    <h1>Den&#xAD;mark im&#xAD;poses new rules to stem rise in new cases</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200920/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-20"><time>2020-09-20</time></a>
        - <span>TOP OF THE NEWS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>COPEN­HAGEN • Den­mark will lower the limit on pub­lic gath­er­ings to 50 peo­ple from 100 and or­der bars and restau­rants to close early to curb a rise i n new Covid-19 in­fec­tions, Prime Min­is­ter Mette Fred­erik­sen said.</p>
    <p>The coun­try has seen daily in­fec­tions rise in re­cent weeks af­ter re­lax­ing lock­down mea­sures im­posed be­tween March and May. In the last 24 hours to Fri­day, 454 new coro­n­avirus in­fec­tions have been reg­is­tered in Den­mark, close to an April record of 473.</p>
    <p>The re­pro­duc­tion rate, which in­di­cates how many peo­ple one in­fected per­son on av­er­age trans­mits the virus to, is at 1.5 across the coun­try, Ms Fred­erik­sen said on Fri­day.</p>
    <p>Bars and restau­rants will have to close at 10pm.</p>
    <p>The mea­sures took ef­fect yes­ter­day and last un­til Oct 4.</p>
    <p>“At present, the re­stric­tions are not com­pre­hen­sive enough to send the Dan­ish econ­omy back­wards,” Sy­d­bank econ­o­mist Soren Kris­tensen said in a note. “How­ever, it will af­fect the Dan­ish econ­omy and so we might see the recovery los­ing fur­ther mo­men­tum.”</p>


